            <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q">What is VO2 max?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">VO2 max (maximal oxygen uptake) is the maximum amount of oxygen your body can use during intense exercise, measured in milliliters of oxygen per kilogram of body weight per minute (ml/kg/min). It is considered the gold standard measure of cardiovascular fitness and aerobic endurance. Higher VO2 max values indicate greater aerobic capacity and are associated with better health outcomes and athletic performance.</div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q">How is VO2 max measured?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">VO2 max can be measured directly in a lab using a graded exercise test with a metabolic cart that analyzes inhaled and exhaled gases. However, this is expensive and requires specialized equipment. Field tests like the Cooper 12-minute run test, the 1-mile walk test (Rockport), and resting heart rate estimation provide reasonably accurate estimates without lab equipment.</div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q">What is a good VO2 max?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">VO2 max values vary by age and gender. For men aged 20–29, a "good" VO2 max is around 42–45 ml/kg/min, while for women the same age it is around 33–36 ml/kg/min. Elite endurance athletes can have VO2 max values above 70 ml/kg/min (men) or 60 ml/kg/min (women). Values decline naturally with age at about 1% per year after age 25, but regular aerobic training can significantly slow this decline.</div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q">What is the Cooper test?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">The Cooper test is a 12-minute running test developed by Dr. Kenneth Cooper in 1968. You run as far as possible in 12 minutes on a flat surface, then use the distance to estimate VO2 max with the formula: VO2 max = (distance in meters &minus; 504.9) &divide; 44.73. It remains one of the most widely used field tests for aerobic fitness and is used by military and law enforcement agencies worldwide.</div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q">How can I improve my VO2 max?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">The most effective ways to improve VO2 max include high-intensity interval training (HIIT) with intervals of 3–5 minutes at 90–95% max heart rate, threshold training at 80–90% max heart rate for sustained periods, and building an aerobic base with Zone 2 training. Most people can improve VO2 max by 15–20% with consistent training over 8–12 weeks. Training 3–5 times per week with a mix of intensities produces the best results.</div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q">Does VO2 max predict longevity?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">Yes, research strongly links VO2 max to longevity. A landmark 2018 study in JAMA Network Open found that cardiorespiratory fitness (measured by VO2 max) was inversely associated with all-cause mortality with no upper limit of benefit. People in the top 2.5% of fitness had an 80% lower risk of death compared to the least fit group. Improving your VO2 max at any age is associated with reduced risk of cardiovascular disease, cancer, and all-cause mortality.</div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q">Why does VO2 max decrease with age?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">VO2 max declines with age due to several physiological changes: decreased maximum heart rate (about 1 bpm per year), reduced stroke volume, decreased muscle mass and mitochondrial density, and lower oxygen extraction by muscles. The average decline is about 10% per decade after age 30. However, regularly active individuals experience a much slower rate of decline (about 5% per decade), and masters athletes can maintain relatively high VO2 max values well into their 60s and 70s.</div>
            </div>
